title: For Sale:  1892 Model Colt D.A. .41 Navy Revolver
postcontent:
All original parts in very good & clean condition. Have not found ammo to shoot gun. Was gift from late grandfather. Blue plating mostly faded. Small chip at bottom of one grip. Otherwise no scratches or blemishes. Manufacture dates, stamps & logos completely visible. Serial #13185 dates it to 1895. 
Colt "New Navy" revolver was the standard sidearm used by U.S. Naval personnel in the Spanish American War. The U.S. Navy began its search for a new handgun to replace the aging converted 1851 Navy revolvers in 1887. These revolvers had been converted to .38 cal. center-fire in 1873, but were still outdated. The Navy decided to replace the weapon with the Model 1889 .38 cal. Colt revolver, and ordered five thousand of them. The weapon did have a problem in that the cylinder did not have locking notches, which could lead to misfires. Most of these weapons were reworked to correct this problem. In 1892, a new model of the "Colt New Navy" was issued which no longer suffered from this problem. The barrel was also shortened. Minor improvements were again apparently made in 1895." Email for more pictures. Comes with antique leather case.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Just some information for buyers
postcontent: I have noticed a lot of sellers asking near new prices for the firearms they are selling.  It does not matter if you have fired 10,000 rounds or no rounds through your firearm, IT IS STILL USED.  Guns are just like cars, once it is sold for the first time, it becomes USED.  To make sure you are not getting screwed, go to The Gallery of Guns and use the gun genie to check the retail on any firearm before you purchase, but remember the prices there are retail.  Call a gun store and ask what the selling price is on what ever model you are thinking of buying.  One other thing I have a problem with,  if you have a $500.00 gun do not be asking to trade it for a $1000.00 gun, it just makes you look stupid.

title: For Sale:  FN Five_seveN IOM 5.7 Not USG version.
postcontent:
I have for sale my New FN Five_seveN. This is the IOM version which came out before the USG and is no longer produced. It comes with everything from the factory.  Below is information on the different Five_seveN Variants. 


Five-seven DAO
The original Five-seven model was introduced in 1998.  It is now discontinued. The model had no manual safety device and it was double-action only, with a heavy trigger pull of 4.5 to 6.5 daN (10 to 14 lbf); its double-action only trigger was harshly criticized.  The model had a pebbled grip pattern, smoothly-contoured accessory rail, low profile fixed sights and a circular-shaped trigger guard designed to improve gloved use.  It did not have a slide release and the slide was not serrated as on newer variants, but a portion of the slide was instead slightly concave to aid grasping.  The original Five-seven also had slightly different markings, with an FN logo placed on the left side of the frame above the trigger guard. 

Five-seven Tactical
The Five-seven Tactical was introduced shortly after the original double-action only variant, as a single-action alternative.  It had a short and light trigger pull of 2 to 3 daN (4.4 to 6.6 lbf), as on current models.  It also had the addition of an ambidextrous manual safety device (located on each side of the frame, as on current models), and a slide release.  Aside from these differences, the Tactical variant was identical to the original double-action only Five-seven.  It was discontinued following the introduction of the IOM variant.

Five-seven IOM
The Five-seven IOM (Individual Officer Model)  was the first variant of the Five-seven pistol to be offered to civilian shooters, debuting in 2004.  It is now discontinued in favor of the USG variant. The IOM was similar in its basic design to the Tactical version, but differed in that it has a M1913 accessory rail, serrated slide and trigger guard, and fully adjustable sights.  It also incorporated a magazine safety mechanism to prevent the weapon from being fired without a magazine inserted. 

Five-seven USG
The Five-seven USG (United States Government)  is the current version of the Five-seven pistol.  This variant was approved by the ATF as a sporting firearm in 2004, replacing the IOM. The USG retains the changes incorporated in the IOM, but has further modifications. These include a conventionally-shaped (square) trigger guard, tightly checkered grip pattern, and a larger, reversible magazine release.  In addition to the standard black finish, this model is available with a flat dark earth frame finish (as the Five-seven FDE) and an olive drab green frame finish (as the Five-seven ODG).  In addition to the standard adjustable sights, this model is also offered with low profile fixed sights. title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare Antique Remington Model 51 .380 Pistol, Reduced!
postcontent:
Hello, I have a very rare, antique Remington Model 51 semi-automatic pistol in .380 caliber. It has been in my family for many years but, due to some financial circumstances, I find myself forced to sell. I'm not an expert in such matters, but I'd rate the gun approx. 85% in finish and 95% in function (I've only had it to the range a small handful of times in 10 years and have had three failure-to-eject using cheap ball ammo). There is some wear shown in the bluing on the outside of the gun on the slide, but overall it's in fantastic shape for its age and could easily be made perfect by a bluing/restoration specialist. It is being sold with one original magazine.

Below is a link containing a lot of information on the particular model (including fun facts like General Patton used to carry one in WWII). As per the standards described on the site, the gun was manufactured between 1918-1921 and would make an excellent piece for a collector. The same model listed on Gunbroker without reserves are priced between $650-$1100, but I am asking $5500 to hopefully facilitate a quick sale and not a lot of lowballing. I would be willing to entertain a partial trade for a subcompact in .380 or 9mm (Ruger LCP, Kel-Tec, etc) but I will need $300 cash at minimum in addition. I know there are some people out there that like to email and offer 50% of the asking price-- if this is you, please save both of us the trouble and don't do it. I do have some things I need to take care of, but I will not just give the gun away.

Please don't hesitate to email me with any questions, specific picture requests, etc. If, for some reason, I cannot get the pictures to load on the ad I'll be happy to email them to you.

Thanks a lot!

http://unblinkingeye.com/Guns/Rem51/rem51.html

Savage Model 23B Sporter bolt action rifle chambered in .25-20 Winchester.  The last patent date on the barrel is Nov. 20, 1917  - rifle is likely 1920s(?) vintage with a serial number of 78xxx that my dad owned for more than 40 years.

The rifle has an excellent bore and is in perfect working condition.  It has the original Savage No. 10 tall peep sight that was developed as an option for the Savage Model 19 NRA Target Rifle (.22 cal) as well as the Sporter series (.22, .25-20, .32-20 & .22 Hornet) with the windage and elevation adjustment knobs.  The bluing on the rifle has gone to mostly plum - there is no rust, corrosion, pitting, etc.  The stock appears to be the original finish, it shows field marks and dings but there are no cracks.  The receiver was tapped for a scope mount before my father got it.  It also has the original steel butt plate with the "Savage Quality" Indian-head logo and one original 5-round magazine.

Reloading supplies included with the rifle include:

- An RCBS two piece reloading die set and case.
